In a JavaScript web app, you can't directly access the local file system due to security restrictions imposed by browsers for security reasons (e.g., preventing malicious scripts from accessing user's files). However, there are a few ways to achieve this:

**Method 1: Using the `blob` API and `saveAs`**

You can create a blob object from your text data using the `Blob` constructor, then use the `saveAs` method of the `FileSaver.js` library to save it as a local file.
```javascript
const text = 'Hello World!';
const blob = new Blob([text], { type: 'text/plain' });
const url = window.URL.createObjectURL(blob);
const link = document.createElement('a');
link.href = url;
link.download = 'example.txt';
link.click();
window.URL.revokeObjectURL(url);
```
**Method 2: Using the `FileSaver.js` library**

You can use the `FileSaver.js` library, which provides a simple way to save blobs as files. First, include the library in your HTML file:
```html
<script src="FileSaver.min.js"></script>
```
Then, use the following code to save your text data as a local file:
```javascript
const text = 'Hello World!';
const blob = new Blob([text], { type: 'text/plain' });
FileSaver.saveAs(blob, 'example.txt');
```
**Method 3: Using the `Web Storage` API (Local Storage)**

You can store your text data in local storage using the `localStorage` object. However, this method is not suitable for large amounts of data and has some limitations.
```javascript
const text = 'Hello World!';
localStorage.setItem('example', text);
```
**Method 4: Using a server-side solution**

If you have a backend server, you can send your text data to the server and then retrieve it using an AJAX request. This method is more complex but offers more flexibility.
```javascript
const xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
xhr.open('POST', 'https://your-server.com/save-text', true);
xhr.send(JSON.stringify({ text: 'Hello World!' }));

// On the server-side:
app.post('/save-text', (req, res) => {
  const text = req.body.text;
  // Save the text to a file or database
});
```
Remember that these methods have their own limitations and requirements. Make sure to check the browser compatibility and security implications before implementing any of these solutions in your web app.
